                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14480689" author="paulk" created="Tue, 5 Aug 2014 03:15:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;As per the Groovydoc, you need to create the &lt;tt&gt;mylock&lt;/tt&gt; field yourself if you don&apos;t go with the default (&lt;tt&gt;$lock&lt;/tt&gt; or $&lt;tt&gt;$LOCK&lt;/tt&gt; for static). However, in that case you shouldn&apos;t get a BUG message but a compiler error.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It looks as if we already add the appropriate error but then proceed to try to detect further errors which we can&apos;t do in this case since the field we would do extra checks on is null. And indeed, returning early (as soon as the error is detected) returns the expected behavior. Not sure when that anomaly crept in. I&apos;ll add an extra test to cover that case.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It doesn&apos;t seem to be related to @CS.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14476287" author="paulk" created="Tue, 5 Aug 2014 03:53:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for spotting the issue. Should be fixed now.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14480697" author="paulk" created="Tue, 5 Aug 2014 03:54:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;For the example above, the compilation error message is:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Error during @Synchronized processing: lock field with name &apos;mylock&apos; not found in class A&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
